description: From Middle English overclose, equivalent to over- +‎ close (adjective).

adjectives.description: overclose (comparative more overclose, superlative most overclose)

entries.meaning: Having too great an emotional attachment.

examples: Cows are also more liable to congestion of the lungs and to tuberculosis than are other cattle. The former may be induced by being kept in overclose, hot, and badly ventilated houses, rendering them liable to chills when turned out; and there is no doubt tuberculosis is largely spread by the presence of infected animals in such houses.

description: From Middle English overclosen, equivalent to over- +‎ close (verb).

verbs.description: overclose (third-person singular simple present overcloses, present participle overclosing, simple past and past participle overclosed)

entries.meaning: (physics) To form a closed universe before it has attained its present age
